1. Symmetry does not automatically produce stability

Your intuition that symmetry “should” stabilize things is common, but physics shows that symmetry only guarantees balance, not stability.

Example:
	•	A pencil balanced perfectly upright on its tip is symmetrical in all directions.
	•	Yet it is extremely unstable.

Why? Because stability depends on the shape of the energy landscape, not just symmetry.

Physicists describe this with potential energy:
	•	Stable equilibrium: a minimum (ball in a bowl)
	•	Unstable equilibrium: a maximum (ball on a hill)
	•	Saddle point: stable in some directions, unstable in others

Magnetic fields produce saddle points rather than bowls, which is why the levitation fails without extra mechanisms.

So symmetry and stability are related but not equivalent.

